    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-10-20T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-10-20T17:00:00-05:00" n="772"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d772">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">352.0022/9: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Argentina</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Weddell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Buenos Aires</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-10-20T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >October 20, 1936—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 7:12 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>229. Department’s 139, October 19, 6 p.m.<note n="70" xml:id="d772fn70">Not
                        printed; bat see telegram No. 162, October 19, 6 p.m., to the Third
                        Secretary of Embassy in Spain, <ref target="#pg_743">p. 743</ref>.</note> I
                    today informed the Minister for Foreign Affairs of our Government’s attitude as
                    set forth therein.</p>
                <p>The Minister for Foreign Affairs told me that replies accepting in principle
                    coordinated action by Latin American countries to maintain a common front as
                    regards right of asylum had been received from all these countries. He added
                    that a meeting of the Latin American diplomatic representatives would be held
                    this afternoon to determine the form of action to be taken which he anticipated
                    would be in the shape of telegrams from all Latin American capitals.</p>
                <p>The Minister for Foreign Affairs interprets the visit of President Azaña to
                    Barcelona as a flight. He further considers that the Spanish Government is
                    practically powerless and can give no adequate guarantees and feels strongly
                    that if persons now receiving asylum are expelled, mass executions will
                    follow.</p>
                <p>The Minister also stated that messages from his diplomatic representative in
                    Madrid are being delayed in transmission.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Weddell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
